[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The **2018 Australian ball-tampering scandal**, also known as **Sandpapergate**, was a cricket cheating scandal surrounding the Australian national cricket team.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In March 2018, during the third Test match against South Africa at Newlands in Cape Town, Cameron Bancroft was caught by television cameras trying to rough up one side of the ball with sandpaper to make it swing in flight.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Captain Steve Smith and vice-captain David Warner were found to be involved and both received unprecedented sanctions from Cricket Australia.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Although he was found not to have been directly involved, Australia's coach, Darren Lehmann, announced he would step down from his role following the scandal.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Smith was replaced by Tim Paine as captain in all formats before Aaron Finch took over from Paine in ODIs and T20Is.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In March 2018, the Australia national cricket team toured South Africa to play four Test matches against the South Africa national cricket team.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Entering the third Test, the series was level 1–1.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 24 March 2018, during the third day of the third Test, after the 43rd over of South Africa's second innings, Australia's Cameron Bancroft was shown on the television coverage and on screens at the ground appearing to rub the ball with a small yellow object.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] After Bancroft realised that he had been seen, he was again shown on the television coverage and on screens at the ground hiding the object in the front of his trousers.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He was then approached by the umpires and he showed them a dark microfibre sunglass pouch from his pocket.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The umpires inspected the ball and chose neither to offer the ball to the South African team to replace it if they wished, nor award them five penalty runs, the options available to the umpires under Law 41.3 of the Laws of Cricket.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] This indicated that the ball had not been altered in any noticeable way.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] At the time, South Africa was 129/2 with a 185 run lead.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] At the press conference at the end of the day's play, Bancroft, accompanied by Australia's captain, Steve Smith, admitted that he was shown attempting to alter the condition of the ball using a short length of yellow adhesive tape to which dirt and grit had adhered, forming an abrasive surface.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Five days later, and after an investigation into the incident by Cricket Australia, he admitted it was sandpaper, which cricketers use to maintain their bats.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Smith also admitted that he knew of the plan in advance of Bancroft's actions.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Smith said that the plan was made during the lunch break by the "leadership group", which he did not name.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Smith said it was a "big mistake", and when questioned by the media, said that he would not be standing down as captain of the team.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Andy Pycroft, the match referee, charged Bancroft with a Level 2 offence of attempting to alter the condition of the ball.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] David Richardson, CEO of the International Cricket Council (ICC), charged Smith with "conduct of a serious nature that is contrary to the spirit of the game".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Smith accepted the charge and the proposed sanction of two suspension points, which equated to a ban for the next Test match, four demerit points being added to his record, and was fined 100% of his match fee.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Bancroft accepted the charge against him, was handed three demerit points and fined 75% of his match fee.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Following Smith's admission, Australia's Prime Minister at that time, Malcolm Turnbull, said it was a "shocking disappointment".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He phoned Cricket Australia (CA) Board chairman David Peever directly to express that disappointment and concern, saying that there has to be the strongest action taken.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The Australian Sports Commission requested that Smith stand down immediately, and the incident was widely condemned by former international players and officials.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In a press release dated 25 March 2018, CA CEO James Sutherland apologised to fans and confirmed that both Smith and Warner had agreed to stand down from their roles of captain and vice-captain respectively for the remainder of the match.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In the same release, David Peever announced that Tim Paine, the team's wicket-keeper, had been endorsed by the Board of CA to step in as acting captain, and Smith and Warner would take to the field under him.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] South Africa went on to win the Test match by 322 runs with Australia dismissed for 107 in the fourth innings.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Cricket Australia launched its own investigation into the incident, led by Executive General Manager Team Performance, Pat Howard, with CA Senior Legal Counsel and Head of Integrity Iain Roy.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] CA CEO James Sutherland joined the investigators in South Africa.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 27 March 2018, before the findings of that investigation were handed down, opening batsman Matt Renshaw was recalled to the squad from Australia ahead of the fourth Test.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 27 March 2018, Sutherland announced that as a result of the preliminary investigation Smith, Warner and Bancroft had been charged with bringing the game into disrepute, suspended and would be sent home.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He said that further sanctions against the three players would be announced within 24 hours, and that CA was satisfied that no one else was involved.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He added that as well as Renshaw, opening batsman Joe Burns and all-rounder Glenn Maxwell were added to the squad to replace them, and confirmed that Paine had been appointed captain for the fourth Test.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] There was no announcement about the vacant vice-captain position.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] South Africa dominated the fourth Test against the depleted Australian team, winning by 492 runs to inflict Australia's second heaviest defeat by runs, and winning the series 3–1.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] During a meeting on 28 March 2018, lasting over two hours, the Cricket Australia Board considered the report.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Warner was found to be responsible for the development of the plan to alter the condition of the ball and instructing Bancroft on how to do it, including demonstrating the technique to him.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He was also found to have failed to prevent the plan being implemented, misled match officials by concealing his knowledge of the plan and not voluntarily reporting his involvement.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He received a twelve-month suspension from "all international and domestic cricket" and he "will not be considered for team leadership positions ever again." Warner faced significant criticism from many individuals, including his fellow countrymen, who held him responsible for the entire scandal.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In the Amazon documentary series about the scandal, *The Test*, Warner opened up on his struggles and road to getting the respect he lost back in the 12 month ban period he served.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He received a twelve-month suspension "from all international and domestic cricket" and he "will not be considered for team leadership positions until a minimum of 12 months after the conclusion of [his suspension] from international and domestic cricket.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Bancroft was found to be a party to the plan to tamper with the ball, that he carried out Warner's instructions, tried to conceal the evidence and made statements to mislead match officials and the public.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He received a nine-month suspension from "all international and domestic cricket" and he "will not be considered for team leadership positions until a minimum of 12 months after the conclusion of [his suspension] from international and domestic cricket.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] As well, "[a]ll three players will be permitted to play club cricket and will be encouraged to do so to maintain links with the cricket community.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Ahead of the decision, Smith and Warner had stepped down as captains of the Rajasthan Royals and Sunrisers Hyderabad respectively in the 2018 Indian Premier League (IPL).
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 28 March 2018, the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) announced that neither Smith nor Warner would be able to play in the 2018 IPL.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Bancroft was contracted to play for English side Somerset in the 2018 County Championship season.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 29 March 2018, Somerset announced that "Bancroft will not be our overseas player for the 2018 season" and that "the club's best interests were at the centre of our decision".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Western Australian Cricket Association CEO Christina Matthews confirmed that under their current rules Bancroft could not play grade cricket because of his suspension.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] However, she added, a rule change was under consideration.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Sutherland specifically addressed repeatedly broadcast footage of coach Darren Lehmann.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] It showed him on a walkie-talkie to 12th man Peter Handscomb at the side of the field after the visual of Bancroft was broadcast.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Hanscomb then ran onto the field to speak with Bancroft.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Sutherland said that the CA investigators were satisfied that Lehmann "sent a message to say 'What in the hell is going on?'– he didn't use 'hell', he used another word", referring to an expletive and that he was not aware of the plan.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Warner was the first to respond publicly.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In a tweet dated 29 March 2018, he apologised for his part in the incident, and took responsibility for his role in it.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He said that he would spend some time with his family, friends and trusted advisers, and would make another statement in the coming days.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He later arrived at Sydney Airport with his wife and two young daughters, and when confronted by media, repeated that he would make a statement in the coming days, and that his priority was to get his family home.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Bancroft arrived in Perth on 29 March 2018, and gave a press conference at the WACA.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] An emotional Bancroft expressed disappointment, regret and remorse, admitting that he had failed as a role model and in the eyes of the broader community, and that when confronted on the field by the umpires and media about his actions he panicked.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He asked for forgiveness and said that he would be contributing back to the community.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In a press conference at Sydney Airport, a tearful Smith started by saying that he had nothing to add to Cricket Australia's report.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He added, "I know I will regret this for the rest of my life.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Australia's coach Darren Lehmann was cleared by the investigation of any wrongdoing or involvement in the scandal, and said that he would not resign.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Of the findings and sanctions, he said that he was "embarrassed" and "disappointed", adding that he hoped people would give all three players a second chance.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] However, on the same day that the three players returned home, Lehmann announced that he would step down from his role after the conclusion of the fourth Test in Johannesburg.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 31 March 2018, an emotional Warner gave a press conference in Sydney.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In it, he described his actions as "inexcusable" and "deeply regrettable".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He apologised for the breach of trust and his actions, accepting full responsibility for the part he played in the incident, and said that the next twelve months would be a tough and emotional time for him.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] His priority at this time would be the well-being of his family.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] While he hoped to play for Australia again, he was resigned for it not to happen.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He said he would spend the coming weeks and months looking at himself "as a man", and would seek advice and expertise to make "serious changes".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He supported a CA investigation into the culture of the Australian cricket side.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] When asked, he said that he would sit down with family, friends and advisers before deciding on his playing future.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Some noted that he deflected multiple questions about whether he was the ringleader of the plan or others' involvement in it.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In the press release announcing the findings and sanctions, Cricket Australia summarised the review process.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] It was reported on 31 March 2018 that Bancroft had sought legal advice and was considering his options.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] It was further reported on 1 April 2018 that all three had sought legal advice and were considering their actions, and importantly that while they all acknowledged erring in Cape Town, they had not formally accepted or challenged their charges or their sanctions issued by CA.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] It was also reported that Smith and Warner were expected to push for a relaxation of the sanctions, particularly to allow them to play domestic cricket in Australia and overseas.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] James Sutherland of CA had previously said that the legal advice they had received was that they did not have jurisdiction requiring other national cricketing bodies to enforce the sanctions.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] "Under the code we didn't have any clear authority over domestic matches played overseas," he said.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 4 April 2018, Steve Smith confirmed that he would not challenge the sanctions.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In a tweet, he said "I would give anything to have this behind me and be back representing my country.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] But I meant what I said about taking full responsibility as Captain of the team.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Also on 4 April 2018, Cameron Bancroft announced that he had advised CA that he accepted the sanction.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He tweeted "Today I lodged the paperwork with Cricket Australia and will be accepting the sanction handed down.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] I would love to put this behind me and will do whatever it takes to earn back the trust of the Australian public.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 5 April 2018, David Warner announced that he had accepted the CA sanctions.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In a tweet, he said "I have today let Cricket Australia know that I fully accept the sanctions imposed on me.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] When announcing the initial findings against Bancroft, Smith and Warner on 27 March 2018, James Sutherland announced that there would also be a deeper review of the "culture and conduct" of Australia's professional cricket teams.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The terms of reference of that inquiry would be to "find a means by which supporters of Australian cricket and the wider community can effectively refresh their commitment to the sport".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Further details of the review would be forthcoming, but it would seek input from "relevant experts", especially to determine how the culture of the Australian men's test side arrived at the point at which it has found itself.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He was expected to be joined by two former players and two current players on a panel, with that quartet unnamed at the time.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] That process would form part of the wide-ranging review, which would provide recommendations to the Cricket Australia board.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Peter Collins, Director of the Centre for Ethical Leadership and a consultant on ethics, leadership and organisational change would act as a "facilitator" for the process.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Peever added that the review will take "whatever time is necessary".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The chief executive of the ICC, Dave Richardson, addressed a news conference on 27 April 2018 about harsher punishments for ball-tampering and other misbehaviour.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Before the start of play of the fourth Test between Australia and South Africa on 30 March 2018, newly appointed Australian captain Tim Paine, with the support of his players, approached South African captain Faf du Plessis.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] After the national anthems were played, both teams shook hands on the field as a gesture of goodwill and respect.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Paine hoped that this would become a ritual that symbolises the new direction and attitude his team would be taking after the fallout from Cape Town.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] While no one contended that the charges and findings against Bancroft, Smith and Warner were not justified, many argued that the sanctions were unprecedented, and that there were flaws in the Cricket Australia (CA) description of the incident.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Some did not separate the event—an attempt at ball tampering—from the wider charge brought against the trio of bringing the game into disrepute.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Du Plessis, who was found guilty of ball tampering in 2013 and again in 2016, sent Smith a text message expressing his sympathy.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He said that "he's one of the good guys and he's just been caught in a bad place".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He agreed when asked if he thought that the sanctions were too harsh.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Shane Warne, former Australian Test bowler who served a one-year ban for breaching the CA drug code in 2003, condemned the trio for engaging in "premeditated cheating", but believed that the public reaction to the incident resulted in excessive penalties being handed down by CA.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] English cricket commentator Mark Nicholas wrote "Clearly the captaincy had to go, and equally clearly the vice-captaincy.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Former Indian captain Sachin Tendulkar argued that the right decision had been made to uphold the integrity of the game, adding "Winning is important but the way you win is more important." However he defended them, saying that the Australian cricketers have dealt with enough criticism.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He also urged media and cricket fans to spare thoughts for their families and that they should be given some breathing space.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Former South African player Herschelle Gibbs said, "Hard scenes watching the interviews.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Former Australian captain and commentator Ian Chappell said that CA were right to ban Smith and Warner for twelve months, adding that he did not expect Smith would captain Australia again because he had lost the respect of the players.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On the duration of the ban, he said "if they would have only given six months to them and they tried to play in Australia's next summer, the booing and crowd reaction would have been so bad.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Former England captain Michael Vaughan thought the bans too harsh, but noted that CA had sent a message to players.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Former Australian batsman Tom Moody believed that the punishment did not fit the crime.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Indian commentator Harsha Bhogle said that "I honestly do not believe any other country would have handed its captain and lead player a one-year ban for attempted ball-tampering." Meanwhile, former Indian batsman and commentator Sanjay Manjrekar was not surprised by the sanctions.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Other cricketers came out in support of the banned players, saying that punishment was too harsh, including Harbhajan Singh, Russel Arnold, Michael Di Venuto and Adam Hollioake.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Gautam Gambhir, the former captain of the IPL side Delhi Daredevils commented that the sanctions imposed on Smith and Warner are quite harsh, and suspected that both may have paid for their roles in a 10-month pay dispute with CA that was resolved in August 2017.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In a tweet he asked the Australian media and the public to spare thoughts for the families of the disgraced cricketers rather than mocking them.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Some criticised CA for its handling of the incident.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Cape Town change room is a very small place!" Michael Vaughan was similarly unconvinced, suggesting that Cricket Australia has only made things worse for itself by finding that only three players were involved.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Former England wicket-keeper Matt Prior said the official explanation didn't match up with his experiences of how teams work.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Former England all-rounder Andrew Flintoff was skeptical that other Australian players, particularly the bowlers, were not involved.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Former England batsman Kevin Pietersen was unconvinced that coach Darren Lehmann did not know of the plan, while BBC broadcaster Jonathan Agnew believed that there were contradictions in the official narrative.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Many demanded a comprehensive explanation from CA, and demanded that they take steps to protect the long term reputation of the sport they had invested in.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 29 March 2018, Magellan Financial Group terminated its three-year naming rights sponsorship agreement with CA in response to the ball-tampering scandal.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The contract had two more seasons to run, and was estimated to be worth AU$20 million.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The incident came as CA was negotiating television broadcast rights to all forms of the game for the next six seasons, estimated at one point to be valued at greater than AU$900 million.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Bidding has not been as high as CA expected, and some expect that the ball tampering incident may further affect those negotiations.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 28 March, Smith and Warner were banned from the 2018 edition of the IPL.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Both the players were going to make A$2.4 million.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 11 April 2018, Cricket Australia announced the list of 20 players who have been awarded national contracts for 2018–19.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Bancroft, Smith and Warner were not on that list, and they were not mentioned in the media release.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In April 2018, Surrey head coach and former Australian cricketer Michael Di Venuto stated that his county would be willing to sign either Smith or Warner during their ban from international cricket.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The LG Electronics company in Australia announced that they had chosen not to renew their personal sponsorship of Warner on 27 March 2018, citing "recent events".
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Warner had been in a commercial arrangement with LG since 2014.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] That arrangement was in its final weeks and was being considered for renewal at the time of his suspension.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] As well as this incident, his behaviour came under the spotlight during the first Test of the tour after the dismissal of South African batsman AB de Villiers.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] He was then involved in a highly publicised personal and escalating verbal altercation with South African batsman Quinton de Kock as they were leaving the field.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Warner's teammates intervened to separate them.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Both were charged by the match referee and penalised.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Earlier in this Test, Warner was involved in a heated exchange with a spectator after being dismissed in Australia's first innings.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The spectator was ejected from the ground.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 29 March 2018, sporting apparel company ASICS terminated their commercial arrangements with Warner and Bancroft.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The Commonwealth Bank terminated their brand ambassador arrangement with Smith, as did Sanitarium for whom Smith was an ambassador for their Weet-Bix product.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Bancroft was the first of three banned players to return to Australian professional cricket.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] On 30 December 2018, he represented the Perth Scorchers in the 2018–19 Big Bash League season.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In the match he scored two runs from three balls, with the Hobart Hurricanes going on to win the game by six wickets.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The bans on Smith and Warner ended on 29 March 2019, coinciding with the date of the fourth One Day International (ODI) match of Australia's series against Pakistan in the United Arab Emirates, however neither made their international return until the first match of the 2019 Cricket World Cup.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The trio made their returns to the Test arena at Edgbaston on 1 August in the first Test of the 2019 Ashes series, with Smith's scores of 144 and 142 earning him the man of the match award as Australia beat England by 251 runs.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] The players had sandpaper waved at them by the English fans during the match.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] In February 2020, Smith and Warner were named in Australia's limited overs squads for their tour to South Africa.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] They both played in the opening Twenty20 International (T20I) match of the tour, the first time they had represented Australia in South Africa since their bans.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] Cricket Australia reportedly reopened an investigation into the scandal in 2021 after Bancroft hinted that some bowlers also knew about it.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/2018-australian-ball-tampering-scandal] A docu-series *The Test: A New Era for Australia's Team* based on the return of the Australian team after the 2018 ball-tampering scandal was streamed on Amazon Prime Video on 11 March 2020 with 8 episodes.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] The team chairman is former Formula One world champion Alan Jones, backed by general manager and former NASCAR driver Peter Nolan.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] The seat is owned by Formula One talent-spotter come principal engineer Alan Docking through his eponymous racing team organisation.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] Will Power was the team's driver for the opening round at Brands Hatch, scoring a fourth place in the Sprint Race and a second in the Main Race, beaten only by Nelson Piquet Jr. who dominated the weekend.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] Power amassed 16 points for these two results; however, he had already signed for Champ Car's Team Australia and made no further appearance in A1GP.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] His replacement was seat owner Jones' son Christian Jones, who did not fare so well; round two in Germany provided no points and a best finish of fourteenth place.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] The uncompetitive Jones was replaced with Will Davison for round three in Portugal, and despite a qualifying performance of 18th place and a first-lap retirement in the Sprint Race, secured sixth place and five points in the Main Race.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] Davison was maintained for the home round at Eastern Creek Raceway, and again provided a sixth-place Main Race result.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] Davison consistently scored better in the Main Race in his drives, securing a one-point tenth place in the UAE round, although retiring from the main race in Durban.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] Contract obligations again caused a driver change when Davison switched to V8 Supercars; Australia's fourth driver of the season was Marcus Marshall, who scored the team's first podium since the opening round with a third-place finish in Indonesia.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] He also moved into V8 Supercars however, and the driver's seat reverted to Christian Jones, who was again uncompetitive.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] The seat for the last two rounds was awarded to Ryan Briscoe, who matched Power and Marshall's podium feat in the final round in China, with a main race third-place finish.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] In total, Australia's best results were a second place and two third places, for a total of 51 points and 13th place in the first-ever A1GP championship.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] Although Team Australia managed to secure three podium finishes during the 2006-07 season, they still finished the championship in 13th position with 25 points.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] Team Australia finished the 2007–08 season in 17th position, but did manage to score points in both the Sprint and Feature races of their home race.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] In the 2008–09 season, Team Australia scored their first ever fastest lap in the final race of the season, however just narrowly missed out on beating New Zealand in the final standings, finishing 8th.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/a1-team-australia] (key), "spr" indicates the Sprint Race, "fea" indicates the Feature Race.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] The **ACT Comets** (also known as the **Canberra Comets**) are a cricket team that represent the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] The Comets are the premier team of the Cricket ACT who are affiliated with Cricket Australia.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] The ACT Comets were participants in the Australian domestic limited-overs Mercantile Mutual Cup competition.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] They did not, however, field a team in the four-day Sheffield Shield competition.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] Their Mercantile Mutual Cup involvement lasted from the 1997–98 season to the 1999–2000 season.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] It was found that there was insufficient local support at that time to be financially viable in the first-class and list-A competitions.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] Former Australian Test bowler Merv Hughes was brought out of retirement to help ACT, as was former Test batsman Mike Veletta.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] Australian internationals Brad Haddin and Nathan Lyon played for the Comets.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] Former Australian Test batsman Michael Bevan was born in Canberra and played cricket with the Weston Creek club, but did not play for the Comets.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] Faunce was instrumental in bringing cricket to the Canberra-Queanbeyan region in the 1830s and died while playing the game at the Queanbeyan Market reserve (now Queen Elizabeth Park).
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] There have been 25 players to play 50 or more games for the ACT.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] Four players have reached 100, while Peter Solway is the only to have reached 150 games.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] Today, the team represents ACT in the lower-level Second XI competition, a reserve grade to the Sheffield Shield.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] The Comets finished the 2005–06 season in fourth place with two outright wins.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-comets] The Comets took out their first ever title in the 2010–11 season.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] The **Australian Capital Territory women's cricket team**, also known as the **Intravision ACT Meteors**, is the women's representative cricket team for the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] They play most of their home games at Manuka Oval, Canberra and they also use Phillip Oval, Canberra.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] They compete in the Women's National Cricket League (WNCL), the premier 50-over women's cricket tournament in Australia.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] They previously played in the now-defunct Australian Women's Twenty20 Cup and Australian Women's Cricket Championships.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Australian Capital Territory's first recorded match was against Queensland in the Australian Women's Cricket Championships on 27 to 28 December 1978, which they won on first innings.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] With the exception of 1980–81, they subsequently competed in every Australian Women's Cricket Championships up to and including its penultimate season in 1994–95.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Their best finish came in 1992–93, when they drew the third-place playoff with Western Australia but secured third place based on first innings score.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Australian Capital Territory joined the Australian Women's Twenty20 Cup and the WNCL in 2009–10, finishing a respectable third in both competitions.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Australian Capital Territory finished fourth in the 2013–14 Twenty20 Cup and qualified for the semi-finals, where they met New South Wales.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Australian Capital Territory won the match by 12 runs thanks to six wickets from Rhiannon Dick.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] However, they lost the final to Queensland by seven wickets after scoring only 107 batting first.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Prior to joining the WNCL, Australian Capital Territory played their home games at a number of grounds in Canberra, including Kingston Oval, Reid Oval, Manuka Oval, Stirling Oval, Kaleen Oval, Boomanulla Oval, O'Connor Oval, Deakin West Ground and St Edmund's College Oval.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] After joining the WNCL in 2009–10, Australian Capital Territory used Manuka Oval for all of their home matches until 2012.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] In 2012 and 2013 they played home matches at Freebody Oval in Queanbeyan, Chisholm Oval in Canberra and Robertson Oval in Wagga Wagga.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Since 2014 they have resumed playing at the Manuka Oval for the majority of their matches.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] They have also started to use Phillip Oval, Canberra, playing their first match there against England on 28 January 2020.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] They played their five 2020–21 WNCL home games and their six 2021–22 WNCL home games at Phillip Oval (now also known as EPC Solar Park).
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] In the 2022–23 WNCL, they split their home matches between Phillip Oval and Manuka Oval.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Based on squad announced for the 2023/24 season.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/act-meteors] Players in **bold** have international caps.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] Griffith represented his native state of Tasmania between 2002 and 2010, and was a member of Tasmania's first-ever Sheffield Shield winning team in 2006–07.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] He took 158 first-class wickets for Tasmania; at the time of his retirement he was the fifth-highest wicket taker in the state's history.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] He also represented Australia A in limited overs cricket and had a spell playing in England for Leicestershire.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] As his career became increasingly affected by injuries, he retired in May 2011 at the age of 33.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] In 2011 Adam immediately moved into coaching, first as the bowling coach for the Western Warriors, working under Mickey Arthur.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] When Arthur was appointed the coach of Australia, Griffith was promoted to the role of Western Australia's assistant coach.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] Griffith was named the Australian bowling coach on 15 April 2016.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] After working with Justin Langer at the Western Warriors and Perth Scorchers, he was chosen after Craig McDermott stepped down after the World 20.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] On 27 April 2017 Griffith was appointed head coach of Tasmania.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/adam-griffith] He is currently serving as the fast bowling coach of Royal Challengers Banglore cricket team in IPL from 2020.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] The **Australia A men's cricket team** is a cricket team representing Australia.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] It is currently used to develop young players and prepare them for the Australian national cricket team, though has seen participation from older, or more established players, as preparation for upcoming series.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] Originally playing as tour matches alongside the main Australian side, the team has since expanded to participating in their own tours.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] Australia had sent Second XI teams on overseas tours before—such as their tours of New Zealand in 1949–50 and 1959–60.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] These teams would consist of players on the fringes of national selection.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] In 1994, this team was given an official name, when the 1994–95 Australian Tri-Series was expanded to involve four teams instead of three, with the addition of "Australia A" to the pre-established Australia, England and Zimbabwe.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] This Australia A team was made up of younger players as part of the selection process for the 1996 Cricket World Cup, with Ricky Ponting, Michael Bevan and Paul Reiffel going from the Australia A side in these games to the squad for the World Cup as David Boon, Tim May and Phil Emery missed out.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] Games involving Australia A are not official One Day Internationals but are included in the List A statistics when that classification was made official by the International Cricket Council in 2006.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] During this series, players would regularly be swapped between the 'A' team and the national team.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] The team originally played 50-over cricket until their first-class debut against the South Africa national team in 1997.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] They participated in their first solo tour in 1998, touring Scotland and Ireland.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] This is a list of every player who has played for the Australia A team since 12 May 2025.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] Players who have already made their debut for the Australian team are in **boldface**.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] Renshaw captained Australia A in List A for Sri Lanka A's tour of Australia in 2025.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] Sangha captained Australia A in first-class for Sri Lanka A's tour of Australia in 2025.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] Edwards captained Australia A for the second and third List A matches in Australia A's tour of India in 2025–26.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] Sutherland captained Australia A for the first List A match in Australia A's tour of India in 2025–26.
[src:australia-a-cricket-team/australia-a-cricket-team] The following coaching panel was named ahead of Sri Lanka A's tour of Australia in 2025, as of June 2025.
